Anglo American, Heineken, Sanofi-Aventis: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   J e n n i f e r   A .   J o h n s o n
-- 
2011-02-16T05:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-15/anglo-american-heineken-sanofi-aventis-europe-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index climbed 0.1 percent to 289.44.
The Stoxx 50 Index gained 0.5 percent to 2,741.36. The Euro
Stoxx 50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, rose 0.4
percent to 3,030.46.    Aeroports de Paris  (ADP FP): The operator of the French
capital’s main airports said January passenger traffic rose 5.5
percent to 6.24 million. The shares fell 0.5 percent to 64.51
euros.    Anglo American Plc  (AAL LN): The London-based mining and
natural resources company said it completed the sale of its
Lisheen zinc mine in Ireland to Vedanta Resources Plc for $546
million in cash. The shares dropped 3.8 percent to 3,306.5
pence.    AS Roma SpA  (ASR IM): One of the Italian soccer club’s
owners, Compagnia Italpetroli SpA, said a group of U.S.
investors led by Thomas DiBenedetto will have 30 days to hold
exclusive talks aimed at acquiring the team. The shares lost 0.5
percent to 1.16 euros.  Brit Insurance Holdings NV (BRE LN): Apollo Global
Management and CVC Capital Partners Ltd. received approval from
the Financial Services Authority and Lloyd’s of  London  for their
888 million-pound ($1.4 billion) takeover of  Brit Insurance
Holdings NV . The shares fell 0.5 percent to 1,055 pence.    Eni SpA  (ENI IM): Russia’s OAO Gazprom Neft will sign an
agreement to enter the Italian oil company’s Elephant oil
project in Libya, Russia President Dimitry Medvedev’s foreign
policy aide Sergei Prikhodko told reporters in Moscow before
talks between Medvedev and Italian Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi. Eni’s stock rose 0.7 percent to 18.4 euros.    Eutelsat Communications  (ETL FP): The world’s third-largest
satellite company said it signed a 12-year contract with
Mediaset for its Hot Bird satellite. The shares fell 0.3 percent
to 28.90 euros.    Heineken NV  (HEIA NA): The world’s third-largest brewer may
say full-year net income rose to 1.33 billion euros ($1.8
billion), according to the average of 18 analyst estimates
compiled by Bloomberg, from 1.02 billion euros a year earlier.
Heineken climbed 1.6 percent to 36.89 euros.    Imerys SA  (NK FP): The world’s biggest producer of minerals
used to whiten paper and add colors to paint said full-year net
income rose to 240.8 million euros from 41.3 million euros a
year earlier. The Paris-based company is. Chief Financial
Officer Michel Delville said the company may be interested in
buying a talc unit put up for sale by Rio Tinto Plc. The shares
dropped 1.6 percent to 51.64 euros.    Lagardere SCA  (MMB FP): The media group’s initial public
offering of Canal Plus France may raise more than 1.35 billion
euros ($1.8 billion), exceeding Lagardere’s earlier
expectations, two people with knowledge of the matter said. The
shares rose less than 0.1 percent to 33.08 euros.  M6  Metropole Television SA  (MMT FP): The television company
said full-year net income rose 13 percent to 157.10 million
euros as sales increased to 1.45 billion euros from 1.37 billion
euros. The company said it will pay a dividend of one euro per
share. The shares dropped 0.5 percent to 18.11 euros.    Sanofi-Aventis SA  (SAN FP): The drugmaker may announce an
agreement to buy Genzyme Corp. for $74 a share, said two people
with knowledge of the matter. Sanofi also plans to make
additional payments tied to the performance of Genzyme’s
multiple sclerosis drug, the people said. The shares dropped 0.3
percent, to 49.80 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
